  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best \"off the beaten path\" places to see in France?",
  "response": "France is home to numerous lesser-known destinations that can make for unique and memorable experiences away from the typical tourist trails. Here are some suggestions for \"off the beaten path\" places to visit in France:\n\n1. **P\u00e9rouges** - This medieval walled town near Lyon is remarkably preserved, offering visitors a journey back in time with cobblestone streets, ancient buildings, and a rich historical ambiance.\n\n2. **Riquewihr** - Located in Alsace, this picturesque village is famous for its charming half-timbered houses and serene vineyards. It\u2019s an ideal spot for wine aficionados and those looking to experience local culture without the usual crowds.\n\n3. **Gorges du Verdon** - Often referred to as Europe's version of the Grand Canyon, this spectacular river canyon in Provence features turquoise-blue waters, stunning cliffs, and varied outdoor activities like hiking, kayaking, and rock climbing.\n\n4. **Rocamadour** - Perched on a cliffside in the Dordogne region, this medieval village is known for its monolithic churches, pilgrimage sites, and dramatic views.\n\n5. **\u00cele de R\u00e9** - Off the west coast near La Rochelle, this quiet island has charming villages, salt marshes, and sandy beaches. Bike trails and seafood make it a perfect retreat for relaxation.\n\n6. **Dinan** - Situated in Brittany, this fortified town boasts medieval architecture, beautiful gardens, and the ramparts with views over the River Rance. The town's historical charm and local cuisine are very enticing.\n\n7. **Albi** - Located in Southern France in the Occitanie region, Albi is renowned for its striking Sainte-C\u00e9cile Cathedral and the Toulouse-Lautrec Museum, nestled within a UNESCO World Heritage site.\n\n8. **Annecy** - Known as the \"Venice of the Alps,\" Annecy is a stunning lakeside town with an intertwining network of canals, medieval buildings, and mountain views, providing a peaceful respite not far from the more visited regions of Chamonix and Geneva.\n\n9. **Chartres** - Famous for its cathedral and quaint old town, Chartres offers a rich historical experience without the overwhelming crowds found in Paris. The labyrinth and the stained glass windows of Chartres Cathedral are must-see wonders.\n\n10. **Les Calanques** - These stunning cliffs and fjords located between Marseille and Cassis offer extraordinary scenery and secluded beaches, perfect for hikers and nature enthusiasts.\n\nExploring these destinations can provide a quieter, more intimate perspective on France, while still immersing visitors in the country\u2019s rich culture, history, and natural beauty.",
